(457, 1, '2014-06-12 11:34:18', '2014-06-12 04:34:18', 'Jakarta - Presiden Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono (SBY), Selasa 19 November 2013, resmi meluncurkan Cetak Biru Literasi Keuangan Indonesia. Presiden mengatakan panduan ini adalah acuan untuk meningkatkan pemahaman bagi para pemangku kepentingan jasa keuangan.<!--more-->\r\nDiharapkan panduan itu menjadi gerakan literasi yang membuat masyarakat lebih "melek" soal jasa keuangan. "Masyarakat kita banyak yang ada di luar dan pinggiran jasa keuangan ini, mari kita tarik masuk," ujar SBY dalam sambutan peluncuran itu di Jakarta.\r\n\r\nStrategi nasional ini adalah rangkaian proses atau aktivitas untuk meningkatkan keyakinan konsumen dan masyarakat luas agar mampu mengelola keuangannya dengan lebih baik.\r\n\r\nPresiden berharap Otoritas Jasa Keuangan (OJK) dapat melakukan sinergi dengan para pemangku kepentingan, sehingga strategi nasional ini dapat tepat sasaran\r\n"Ajaklah para Gubernur, Bupati, libatkan para semua pemangku kepentingan," kata SBY.\r\n\r\nTiga masalah\r\nKetua Dewan Komisioner OJK, Muliaman D Hadad di tempat yang sama mengungkapkan, cetak biru ini terdiri dari tiga pilar utama. Pertama, edukasi dan kampanye literasi keuangan. "Kegiatan itu menyasar mulai dari ibu rumah tangga hingga seluruh elemen masyarakat lainnya," kata Muliaman.\r\n\r\nKedua, penguatan infrastruktur literasi keuangan. Dalam hal ini OJK telah menyiapkan situs dan mobil literasi yang nantinya akan disebar di seluruh provinsi untuk memberikan edukasi pada masyarakat.\r\n\r\nKetiga, pengembangan produk dan layanan literasi keuangan. Hal itu dilakukan dengan menyampaikan produk-produk dan jasa keuangan ke masyarakat. "Saat ini sudah banyak yang terjangkau, di antaranya asuransi mikro yang dengan polis murah," kata Muliaman.\r\n\r\nDalam kesempatan terpisah, Menteri Koordinator Bidang Perekonomian Hatta Rajasa, Selasa 19 November 2013, menyambut baik diluncurkannya Literasi Keuangan Indonesia. Apalagi, mengingat kenyataan tentang pemahaman masyarakat Indonesia terhadap akses keuangan masih rendah.\r\n\r\nMenurut Hatta, berdasarkan laporan dan pengamatan selama ini, pemahaman masyarakat khususnya yang berusia produktif terhadap akses keuangan masih sekitar 40 persen. Sisanya, buta informasi. Artinya, ada kurang lebih 60 persen masyarakat usia produktif yang belum bisa memanfaatkan jasa keuangan dengan baik.\r\n\r\n"Nah, disitulah peran Otoritas Jasa Keuangan (OJK) yang penting," ujar Hatta kepada VIVAnews.\r\n\r\nIni menunjukkan ada masalah dalam pemahaman masyarakat terhadap produk dan jasa keuangan selama ini, sehingga tidak antusias memanfaatkan berbagai produk seperti fasilitas pembiayaan maupun pinjaman atau kredit yang ditawarkan perbankan maupun jasa keuangan lainnya.\r\n\r\nHatta menengarai masyarakat lebih senang menabung atau mengumpulkan uang untuk memenuhi keperluannya, ketimbang memperoleh pinjaman bank.\r\n\r\nBanyak bank yang menawarkan produk pembiayaan maupun fasilitas usaha, terutama menyasar sektor usaha kecil dan menengah. Namun, kredit permodalan bagi UKM pun belum banyak dimanfaatkan oleh masyarakat.\r\n\r\n"Kredit ini bukan sekedar utang. Kan bisa menabung, membayar dengan gampang, bisnisnya jalan," kata Hatta.\r\n\r\nOleh karena itu, Hatta optimistis dengan kehadiran panduan Literasi Keuangan Indonesia ini, akses masyarakat terhadap produk dan jasa keuangan di Indonesia dapat meningkat. Apabila itu terjadi, pertumbuhan ekonomi Indonesia di masa mendatang bisa lebih berkualitas.\r\n\r\nEkonom PT Bank Mandiri Tbk, Destry Damayanti, menilai bahwa pertumbuhan industri perbankan yang pesat di Indonesia ternyata tidak dibarengi dengan akses layanan perbankan ke masyarakat. Kondisi itu membuat sektor keuangan di Indonesia mengalami keterbatasan dalam menjangkau masyarakat kelas bawah.\r\n\r\nMenurut Destry, saat ini, di Indonesia baru 20 persen penduduk berusia 15 tahun yang memiliki akses ke sektor keuangan. Tak hanya itu, dari 230 juta jiwa penduduk Indonesia, kurang lebih hanya 2 juta orang atau kurang 1 persen jumlah penduduk yang bisa mengakses pasar modal.\r\n\r\nPerbandingannya dengan negara maju sangat jauh. "Kalau kita lihat negara maju, hanya 8 persen yang belum punya akses keuangan, sedangkan di negara berkembang 59 persen," ujar Destry.\r\n\r\n"Harus ada langkah meningkatkan kesadaran seluruh stakeholders untuk menciptakan jangkauan perbankan sampai ke masyarakat kecil," kata Destry.\r\n\r\nPada 2012, Destry melanjutkan, penetrasi perbankan Indonesia mengalami penurunan hingga 41 persen. Padahal, pada tahun sebelumnya mencapai 43 persen.\r\n\r\nSementara itu, dari sisi penyaluran kredit kurang lebih masih di kisaran 35 persen dari produk domestik bruto (PDB). Angka ini jauh lebih kecil dari Malaysia yang sudah mencapai 100 persen.\r\n\r\n"Keterbatasan akses keuangan dari masyarakat Indonesia ini perlu mendapat perhatian serius dari para stakeholders. Kami akan coba buka kesadaran perbankan untuk bekerja sama meningkatkan kesadaran finansial masyarakat demi menambah pertumbuhan inklusif," ujarnya.\r\nSulitnya akses\r\nMelihat fakta tersebut, menurut Destry, beberapa faktor yang menjadi kendala di sektor keuangan Indonesia antara lain rendahnya kesadaran dan akses masyarakat terhadap transaksi, tabungan, kredit, dan asuransi. "Sektor keuangan kita ini ruang untuk tumbuhnya besar sekali, mestinya dikembangkan lagi," kata Destry.\r\n\r\nDeputi Gubernur Bank Indonesia (BI), Halim Alamsyah, pernah menyinggung masalah mendasar yang dihadapi usaha mikro, kecil, dan menengah (UMKM) adalah akses permodalan. Berdasarkan data BI, outstanding kredit produktif di sektor UMKM per April 2013 baru mencapai Rp570 triliun atau 19,6 persen dari total kredit perbankan.\r\n\r\nUntuk mengatasinya, kata Halim, BI telah meminta kesediaan perbankan untuk menyalurkan kredit UMKM sebesar 20 persen secara bertahap. Pemberian kredit ini diharapkan dapat menjadi pendorong pertumbuhan ekonomi yang lebih tinggi.\r\n\r\n"Kami tahu tidak semua bank ahli dalam penyaluran kredit UMKM, untuk itu kami sarankan untuk bertahap atau melakukan kerjasama dengan lembaga keuangan yang ahli dalam penyaluran kredit UMKM," kata Halim beberapa waktu lalu di Jakarta.\r\n\r\nBank sentral pun akan memperkuat kebijakan terkait dengan keuangan inklusif dan sektor usaha mikro, kecil, dan menengah (UMKM). Gubernur BI, Agus Martowardojo, Kamis 14 November 2013, menyatakan bahwa kebijakan ini berperan dalam mendorong intermediasi dan efisiensi perbankan.\r\n\r\nMenurut Agus, kebijakan ini nantinya juga berkontribusi dalam penguatan stabilitas sistem keuangan dan mendukung kebijakan di bidang sistem pembayaran. "Kebijakan keuangan inklusif ini difokuskan pada lima strategi," kata Agus di Jakarta.\r\n\r\nLima strategi itu adalah penguatan edukasi keuangan, peningkatan akses, perlindungan konsumen, penyediaan informasi, dan pengaturan stabilitas sistem keuangan maupun rekomendasi kebijakan kepada otoritas terkait. (Vivanews.com)', 'Cetak Biru Menuju Rakyat "Melek" Jasa Keuangan', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '431-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-12 11:34:18', '2014-06-12 04:34:18', '', 431, 'http://perbanas.org/en/431-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(458, 1, '2014-06-12 11:34:50', '2014-06-12 04:34:50', 'Jakarta - President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono (SBY), Tuesday, November 19, 2013, officially launched the Financial Literacy Blueprint Indonesia. The President said this guide is a reference for improving the understanding of the financial services stakeholders.<!--more-->\r\nIt is expected that the guide into literacy movement that makes people more "literate" about financial services. "Our society is that there are many and suburbs outside the financial services, let us pull in," Yudhoyono said in his speech at the launch in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nThis national strategy is a series of processes or activities to improve consumer confidence and the general public to be able to manage their finances better.\r\n\r\nThe President hoped that the Financial Services Authority (FSA) can synergize with the stakeholders, so that the national strategy is to precisely target\r\n"Invite the Governors, Regents, involve all the stakeholders," said SBY.\r\n\r\nThree problems\r\nFSA Chairman of the Board, Hadad D Hadad in the same place revealed, this blueprint consists of three main pillars. First, education and financial literacy campaigns. "Activities that target ranging from housewives to all elements of society," Hadad said.\r\n\r\nSecond, strengthening financial literacy infrastructure. In this case the FSA has set up a website and literacy car which will be distributed throughout the province to provide education to the community.\r\n\r\nThird, product development and financial literacy services. This was done by delivering products and financial services to the public. "We have had a lot of affordable, including micro insurance policy with cheap," Hadad said.\r\n\r\nSeparately, Coordinating Minister for Economic Affairs Hatta Rajasa, Tuesday, November 19, 2013, welcomed the launch of the Indonesian Financial Literacy. Moreover, given the reality of the Indonesian people\'s understanding of access to finance is still low.\r\n\r\nAccording to Hatta, based on reports and observations, especially the old people\'s understanding of access to finance is still earning about 40 percent. The rest, blind information. That is, there are approximately 60 percent of people of reproductive age who have not been able to properly utilize financial services.\r\n\r\n"Well, that\'s where the role of the Financial Services Authority (FSA) is important," Hatta said the headline.\r\n\r\nIt shows there is a problem in people\'s understanding of financial products and services for this, so it is not enthusiastic about utilizing a variety of products such as financing and loan facilities offered by banks or credit or other financial services.\r\n\r\nHatta suggests people prefer to save or raise money to meet his needs, rather than a bank loan.\r\n\r\nMany banks are offering financing products and business facilities, primarily targeting the small and medium enterprise sector. However, capital loans for SMEs was not widely used by the community.\r\n\r\n"Credit is not just debt. Kan can save, pay with easy, business street," said Hatta.\r\n\r\nTherefore, Hatta optimistic with the presence of the Indonesian Financial Literacy guide, public access to financial products and services in Indonesia can be increased. If that happens, Indonesia\'s economic growth in the future could be more qualified.\r\n\r\nEconomist of PT Bank Mandiri Tbk, Destry Damayanti, judging that the rapid growth of the banking industry in Indonesia was not accompanied by access to banking services to the public. Conditions that make the financial sector in Indonesia has limitations in reaching out to the lower classes.\r\n\r\nAccording to Destry, this time, in Indonesia only 20 percent of the population aged 15 years who had access to the financial sector. Not only that, of the 230 million inhabitants of Indonesia, only about 2 million people, or approximately 1 percent of the population can access the capital markets.\r\n\r\nThe comparison with developed countries so far. "If we look at the developed countries, only 8 percent who do not have access to finance, while in developing countries 59 percent," said Destry.\r\n\r\n"There should be measures to increase awareness of all stakeholders to create a range of up to a small community bank," said Destry.\r\n\r\nIn 2012, Destry continued penetration of Indonesian banks have declined by 41 percent. In fact, in the previous year to reach 43 percent.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, on the credit side is still in the range of approximately 35 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). This figure is much smaller than Malaysia which has reached 100 percent.\r\n\r\n"Limited access to finance of Indonesian society is in need of serious attention from the stakeholders. Awareness We will try to open the banking sector to work together to improve the community in order to increase financial awareness of inclusive growth," he said.\r\nDifficulty of access\r\nSeeing this fact, according to Destry, several factors constrain the Indonesian financial sector, among others, lack of awareness and access to transactions, savings, credit, and insurance. "Our financial sector is enormous room for growth, it should be developed further," said Destry.\r\n\r\nDeputy Governor of Bank Indonesia (BI), Halim Alam, never alludes to the fundamental problems faced by micro, small, and medium enterprises (SMEs) is access to capital. Based on BI data, earning outstanding credit in the SME sector by April 2013 reached Rp570 trillion or 19.6 percent of total bank credit.\r\n\r\nTo overcome this, Halim said the central bank had asked banks willingness to lend to SMEs by 20 percent sequentially. Lending is expected to be a driver of higher economic growth.\r\n\r\n"We know not all banks are experts in SME lending, for that we recommend to gradual or cooperation with financial institutions with expertise in SME lending," Halim said some time ago in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nThe central bank will also strengthen policies related to inclusive financial sector and micro, small, and medium enterprises (SMEs). BI Governor Agus Martowardojo, Thursday, November 14, 2013, stating that this policy plays a role in encouraging intermediation and banking efficiency.\r\n\r\nAccording to Agus, this policy will also contribute to strengthening the stability of the financial system and support the policies in the field of payment systems. "Inclusive financial policy is focused on five strategies," Agus said in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nFive strategies it is strengthening financial education, increased access, consumer protection, the provision of information, and the stability of the financial system as well as setting policy recommendations to the relevant authorities. (Vivanews.com)', 'Towards a People\'s Blueprint "Literacy" Financial Services', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '438-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-12 11:34:50', '2014-06-12 04:34:50', '', 438, 'http://perbanas.org/en/438-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(459, 1, '2013-12-24 11:40:13', '2013-12-24 04:40:13', 'Jakarta – The Extraordinary General Meeting of Shareholders of Bank Mutiara, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013, finally decided on a capital increase of 1, 249 trillion rupiahs, which raises the Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) of Bank Mutiara to 14%. This CAR position is in accordance to the provisions of the Internal Capital Adequacy Assesment Process (ICAAP).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe Banking community shows its appreciation towards the step taken by the Indonesia Deposit Insurance Corporation (IDIC) as a shareholder of Bank Mutiara, in support of the healthy growth of the banking industry. The IDIC’s decision for a capital increase is also in line with Banking Laws and the IDIC Law. At the end of 2013, the total asset of Bank Mutiara is estimated to be over 15 trillion rupiahs.\r\n\r\nChairman of the Indonesian Banks Association (PERBANAS), Sigit Pramono, supports the decision of IDIC to increase the capital of Bank Mutiara. “We would have questioned IDIC if they did otherwise. It should be understood that in the case of Bank Mutiara, the position of IDIC is as a shareholder of a bank that was saved. Not as a regulator. So, if Bank Mutiara really needs a capital increase within reason, then IDIC should approve,” he said, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Sigit adds, the law stipulates that IDIC is responsible for the sustainability of the bank taken over until it can be sold again in accordance to the regulations. On the other hand according to several analysts, after the capital increase, the performance of Bank Mutiara is perceived to improve which therefore will increase selling price. (infobanknews.com)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Bankers Support Decision of IDIC to “Save” Bank Mutiara', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'bankers-support-step-lps-save-bank-mutiara', '', '', '2014-06-24 07:59:18', '2014-06-24 00:59:18', '', 0, 'http://perbanas.org/en/?post_type=news&#038;p=459', 0, 'news', '', 0) ;
