(1037, 1, '2014-06-19 13:46:06', '2014-06-19 06:46:06', 'The banking industry is constantly evolving to keep in line with the overall economy. PERBANAS as an organization for banks in Indonesia must also be able to evolve dynamically over time. It aims to broaden the knowledge of its members in the midst of rapid progress in all fields.\r\n\r\nPERBANAS is currently an open organization, its members not only consisting of national private banks as at the beginning of its establishment, but also accepting other types of banks such as state owned banks and Regional Development Banks (BPD). The decision for an open organization was achieved during the 15th financial industry. Congress which was held in Jakarta in 2003, taking into account the developments of the\r\n\r\nWith open membership, PERBANAS is expected to be the only organization in the banking industry, thus making the banking sector increasingly solid in anticipation of problems that may occur now or in the future. This matter is also in accordance to the wishes of the government that there shall not be too many banking organizations in Indonesia.\r\n<p class="text-center" class="in-article-diagram"><a href="http://perbanas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/PBS_Website_LO4_About-StructCom01.gif"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://perbanas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/PBS_Website_LO4_About-StructCom01.gif" alt="[cml_media_alt id=\'1024\']PBS_Website_LO4_About-StructCom01[/cml_media_alt]" width="1000" height="1597" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>CSR / KMPP</h2>\r\nAs an act of its corporate social responsibilty (CSR), Perbanas formed Komite Masyarakat Perbankan Peduli (KMPP) or also called Perbanas Peduli on 14 June 2006. The main goal of KMPP is to give aid to victims of natural disasters.\r\nThe vision and mission of KMPP is none other than an act of compassion from the “PERBANAS” banking community in Indonesia to those who have been devastated by a natural disaster. Therefore during the last few years, all of the members of Perbanas have collectively been committed to implement CSR programs which have a national impact, especially in the field of education.\r\n<h2>PROGRAM OF ACTIVITIES</h2>\r\n<h3>Fixed Program</h3>\r\nReconstruction/renovation of school buildings (elementary) which have been destroyed.\r\n<h3>Short Term Program</h3>\r\n1. <i>Banking Education</i>. Provide educational banking seminars for teachers and students. As a first step, will be implemented at 5 schools which were built by KMPP, which are: SDN Giwangan-Yogya, SDN Kabregan-Bantul, SDN Kotesan-Klaten, SDN Panjalu-Ciamis, and SDN Ngadirejo-Bromo.\r\n\r\n2. <i>Training for Trainers</i>. Provide training for talented individuals to become trainers.\r\n<h3>National Disaster Relief</h3>\r\n1. Fulfilling the needs of disaster victims\r\n\r\n2. Post disaster relief\r\n<h3>Mid Term Program</h3>\r\n1. Provide courses and teach skills in a certain field to communities who need it in order to start a business. Example: cooking, making batik, reflexology, hairdressing or herbal medicine.\r\n\r\n2. Create economically independent villages with one basic form of business. Example: An economically independent village with herbal medicine as its main business.', 'What We Do', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '417-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-19 13:46:06', '2014-06-19 06:46:06', '', 417, 'http://perbanas.org/en/417-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
