cording to each of its own functions.\r\n<h3>Development Cabinet Period (1968-1998)</h3>\r\nEntering the Development Cabinet Period, state owned banks which were previously incorporated into a Single Bank were separated to return operating according to each of its own functions. The liberalization of banks in 1988 facilitated the establishment of new banks, therefore increasing the number of banks significantly. The amendment of rules and political intervention then triggered the downfall of the banking system, causing Indonesia to enter a period of banking and economic crisis in 1998.\r\n<h3>Post Crisis Period (1999)</h3>\r\nThe banking crisis which happened in 1997-1998 caused state owned banks to face major issues as a result of political intervention in the granting of credits and bad management. The government then ordered total restructuring and tightened the regulations, and also gave Bank Indonesia the authority to operate fully according to its function. The consolidation of several state owned banks then eliminated most specific bank functions which were previously adopted. However, BRI and BTN still adopted their specific functions.', 'Banking In Indonesia', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '486-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-20 20:56:31', '2014-06-20 13:56:31', '', 486, 'http://perbanas.org/en/486-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1088, 1, '2014-06-23 09:18:09', '2014-06-23 02:18:09', 'Manado – The Indonesian Banks Association (PERBANAS) and the Humanitarian Banking Society Committee (KMPP), Monday (10/2) provided disaster relief to natural disaster victims in the village of Pinaesaan, Manado. The relief was given by the Head of PERBANAS Regional Branch in North Sulawesi, Ferry A. Keintjem accompanied by Luctor Tapiheru.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nPrior to distributing it to the victims, the relief was officially handed to the Mayor of Manado, G.S. Vicky Lumentul represented by Deputy Mayor Harley A.B. Mangindaan.\r\n\r\n“On behalf of the Mayor, the Manado City Government, and the people of Manado, especially those who are affected by the natural disaster on 15 January, I would like to thank Perbanas who has shown sympathy and compassion towards the disaster victims. This relief has also encouraged us to continue helping the victims,” said Mangindaan, regularly knows as Ai.\r\n\r\nOn a different note, Ai also informed the people of Manado about the working plans of the Manado City Government, who in the next 3 weeks will conduct a total cleanup of all areas including clogged drainage.\r\n\r\n“The Mayor and I hope that through this relief, the people of Manado will be stronger in facing disasters and work together to recover the city of Manado,” he added.\r\n\r\nIn total, PERBANAS and KMPP donated 20 units of water pumps, 200 gas cylinders each weighing 3kg and 1600 items of clothing. Donations from PERBANAS and KMPP will be sent to several different regions affected by the disaster in Manado. (manatoday.com)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Manado City Government Receives Disaster Relief from PERBANAS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '466-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-23 09:18:09', '2014-06-23 02:18:09', '', 466, 'http://perbanas.org/en/466-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1089, 1, '2014-06-23 09:23:48', '2014-06-23 02:23:48', 'Jakarta – The Extraordinary General Meeting of Shareholders of Bank Mutiara, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013, finally decided on a capital increase of 1, 249 trillion rupiahs, which raises the Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) of Bank Mutiara to 14%. This CAR position is in accordance to the provisions of the Internal Capital Adequacy Assesment Process (ICAAP).\n\n<!--more-->\n\nThe Banking community shows its appreciation towards the step taken by the Indonesia Deposit Insurance Corporation (IDIC) as a shareholder of Bank Mutiara, in support of the healthy growth of the banking industry. The IDIC’s decision for a capital increase is also in line with Banking Laws and the IDIC Law. At the end of 2013, the total asset of Bank Mutiara is estimated to be over 15 trillion rupiahs.\n\nChairman of the Indonesian Banks Association (PERBANAS), Sigit Pramono, supports the decision of IDIC to increase the capital of Bank Mutiara. “We would have questioned IDIC if they did otherwise. It should be understood that in the case of Bank Mutiara, the position of IDIC is as a shareholder of a bank that was saved. Not as a regulator. So, if Bank Mutiara really needs a capital increase within reason, then IDIC should approve,” he said, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013.\n\nMoreover, Sigit adds, the law stipulates that IDIC is responsible for the sustainability of the bank taken over until it can be sold again in accordance to the regulations. On the other hand according to several analysts, after the capital increase, the performance of Bank Mutiara is perceived to improve which therefore will increase selling price. (infobanknews.com)\n\n&nbsp;', 'Bankers Support Decision of IDIC to “Save” Bank Mutiara', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '459-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-06-23 09:23:48', '2014-06-23 02:23:48', '', 459, 'http://perbanas.org/459-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1090, 1, '2014-06-23 09:34:31', '2014-06-23 02:34:31', 'Jakarta – The Extraordinary General Meeting of Shareholders of Bank Mutiara, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013, finally decided on a capital increase of 1, 249 trillion rupiahs, which raises the Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) of Bank Mutiara to 14%. This CAR position is in accordance to the provisions of the Internal Capital Adequacy Assesment Process (ICAAP).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe Banking community shows its appreciation towards the step taken by the Indonesia Deposit Insurance Corporation (IDIC) as a shareholder of Bank Mutiara, in support of the healthy growth of the banking industry. The IDIC’s decision for a capital increase is also in line with Banking Laws and the IDIC Law. At the end of 2013, the total asset of Bank Mutiara is estimated to be over 15 trillion rupiahs.\r\n\r\nChairman of the Indonesian Banks Association (PERBANAS), Sigit Pramono, supports the decision of IDIC to increase the capital of Bank Mutiara. “We would have questioned IDIC if they did otherwise. It should be understood that in the case of Bank Mutiara, the position of IDIC is as a shareholder of a bank that was saved. Not as a regulator. So, if Bank Mutiara really needs a capital increase within reason, then IDIC should approve,” he said, in Jakarta, Monday, 23 December 2013.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Sigit adds, the law stipulates that IDIC is responsible for the sustainability of the bank taken over until it can be sold again in accordance to the regulations. On the other hand according to several analysts, after the capital increase, the performance of Bank Mutiara is perceived to improve which therefore will increase selling price. (infobanknews.com)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Bankers Support Decision of IDIC to “Save” Bank Mutiara', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '459-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-23 09:34:31', '2014-06-23 02:34:31', '', 459, 'http://perbanas.org/en/459-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1091, 1, '2014-06-23 09:36:12', '2014-06-23 02:36:12', 'Jakarta – The rapid development of technology in the information and communication sector, as well as globalization in the banking system, has made banks become main targets for money laundering. This is due to the fact that banks still play a strategic role in supporting the financial system in Indonesia.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nAlso, the strict confidentiality of banks is also one of the main considerations for money launderers.\r\n\r\nThus conveyed by banking law analyst, Pradjoto, in a seminar held by the Indonesia Banks Association (PERBANAS) themed “Legal Review on the Role of Banks in Indonesia in Facing Money Laundering and Terrorism Funding”, held in Jakarta, Thursday, 19 December 2013.\r\n\r\nAccording to Pradjoto, it is important to apply the principles of Know Your Customer (KYC) in every bank transaction. Also, there needs to be strong supervision and commitment from the banking board of directors and commissioners, as well as reports to the Financial Transaction Report and Analysis Center (PPATK), should there be any suspicious transactions.\r\n\r\nHead of PERBANAS Law Sector who is also Director of Compliance, Corporate Affairs &amp; Legal at PT Bank CIMB Niaga Tbk, L. Wulan Tumbaleka says, money laundering can now be done by anyone from all levels of society. The techniques used are also more advanced, therefore seeming more competitive with the eradication efforts done by law enforcers.\r\n\r\n“Perbanas calls for the banking society as well as the general public to share their experiences and play an active role in overseeing financial transactions which can potentially be crimes of money laundering or terrorism funding,” says Wulan.\r\n\r\nAs an organization for national banks in Indonesia, Perbanas, through its Law Sector, has given recommendations to the government in the drafting of Banking Laws, recommendations in general as well as specifically concerning money laundering. Direct recommendations from banking practitioners in Indonesia are important to achieve a Banking Law which is appropriate with the needs of the banking industry as well as stakeholders.\r\n\r\nAccording to Wulan, recommendations from Perbanas are based on proposals and ideas from national banks. “Recommendations from Perbanas for the Banking Law have become a commitment for Perbanas in order to achieve a better future for the banking industry,” closed Wulan. (infobanknews.com)\r\n\r\nAs an organization that embodies national banks in Indonesia, Perbanas, through Perbanas Legal Affairs, has provided input to the government in the preparation of the Act (the Act) Banking, both in general and with regard to the crime of money laundering. Direct input from the banking industry in Indonesia, it becomes important for the creation of the Banking Law that really fit the needs of the banking industry and stakeholders.\r\n\r\nInputs given Perbanas, according Wulan, or have previously been proposed based on the idea of ​​national banks. "Inputs from Perbanas to be committed Perbanas Banking Act in order to bring the future of the banking industry better," Wulan lid. (Infobanknews.com)', 'Banks an Easy Target for Money Laundering', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '440-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-23 09:36:12', '2014-06-23 02:36:12', '', 440, 'http://perbanas.org/en/440-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
